 of colonial power. In particular, Jinsoo An examines how South Korean films privileged certain sites, such as the kisaeng house and the Manchurian frontier, generating unique meanings that challenged the domination of the colonial power, and how horror films indirectly explored both the continuing trauma of colonial violence and lingering emotional ties to the colonial order. Espousing the ideology of nationalism while responding to a new Cold War order that positioned Japan and South Korea as political and economic allies, postcolonial cinema formulated distinctive ways of seeing and imagining the colonial past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialism in motion picturesy20th century. 0aImperialism in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalism in motion picturesy20th century. 0aNationalism in motion pictures. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520968103?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968103zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968103/original  a978-3-11-066767-7 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA